Hi everyone.

00:00:18.750 --> 00:00:20.580
AMAR JOSHI: So
thanks for coming in.

00:00:20.580 --> 00:00:23.171
You are Google New
York's favorite chef, one

00:00:23.171 --> 00:00:24.420
of the favorite chefs up here.

00:00:27.180 --> 00:00:29.772
VIKAS KHANNA:
[NON ENGLISH SPEECH]

00:00:29.772 --> 00:00:31.250
AMAR JOSHI: I bet, yeah, right?

00:00:31.250 --> 00:00:33.320
VIKAS KHANNA: I'm
so proud to be here.

00:00:33.320 --> 00:00:35.140
This is my third
time here I guess.

00:00:35.140 --> 00:00:36.120
AMAR JOSHI: Yeah.

00:00:36.120 --> 00:00:39.285
VIKAS KHANNA: Two times I was
just cooking food for everyone.

00:00:39.285 --> 00:00:41.410
And both the times, it
happened to be Diwali, which

00:00:41.410 --> 00:00:42.750
is the big Indian festival.

00:00:42.750 --> 00:00:48.060
So I'm proud to bring a
piece of homeland to America.

00:00:48.060 --> 00:00:48.950
AMAR JOSHI: Nice.

00:00:48.950 --> 00:00:52.530
So we also have food
today from your book.

00:00:52.530 --> 00:00:57.620
It's in Hemispheres at
2pm, so go eat that.

00:00:57.620 --> 00:01:00.670
So you've been in New
York for how many years?

00:01:00.670 --> 00:01:01.860
Like more than few--

00:01:01.860 --> 00:01:05.600
VIKAS KHANNA: I came here
in 2000, December 2nd,

00:01:05.600 --> 00:01:07.210
don't count years.

00:01:07.210 --> 00:01:08.720
AMAR JOSHI: Well--

00:01:08.720 --> 00:01:10.900
VIKAS KHANNA: I'm not
the best with that.

00:01:10.900 --> 00:01:13.000
But it's almost 16
years, 15 years?

00:01:13.000 --> 00:01:14.916
AMAR JOSHI: Do you call
yourself a New Yorker?

00:01:14.916 --> 00:01:16.900
Like do you look at New
York as home or is it--

00:01:16.900 --> 00:01:19.470
VIKAS KHANNA: I was reading
this British, some philosopher,

00:01:19.470 --> 00:01:22.430
who said that, you're
born out of darkness.

00:01:22.430 --> 00:01:23.820
And you come to the world.

00:01:23.820 --> 00:01:27.330
Same thing happened to me when
I got off number 7 train, which

00:01:27.330 --> 00:01:28.850
came out of the tunnel.

00:01:28.850 --> 00:01:30.940
So I felt exactly the same.

00:01:30.940 --> 00:01:32.960
Everyone remembers
coming to New York City.

00:01:32.960 --> 00:01:36.780
The first stop, the moment that
came up, the first side walk,

00:01:36.780 --> 00:01:40.825
the first building they saw,
it's so real, it's like--

00:01:40.825 --> 00:01:42.870
AMAR JOSHI: It's like
you're here finally.

00:01:42.870 --> 00:01:43.953
VIKAS KHANNA: You made it.

00:01:46.130 --> 00:01:47.660
AMAR JOSHI: Nice, yeah.

00:01:47.660 --> 00:01:51.460
So your new book, "Classic and
Contemporary Indian Dishes,

00:01:51.460 --> 00:01:55.820
Indian Harvest," tell
us something about why

00:01:55.820 --> 00:01:57.654
you have a vegetarian book.

00:01:57.654 --> 00:01:59.070
It's all vegetarian
dishes, right?

00:01:59.070 --> 00:02:00.986
VIKAS KHANNA: These are
all vegetarian dishes.

00:02:00.986 --> 00:02:03.840
It's a book by
Bloomsbury USA, and I'm

00:02:03.840 --> 00:02:06.180
very proud for this association.

00:02:06.180 --> 00:02:09.229
I think even the name
is very beautiful.

00:02:09.229 --> 00:02:11.230
It's about harvest.

00:02:11.230 --> 00:02:14.380
The most essentials of our life.

00:02:14.380 --> 00:02:15.980
It's something of
gratitude, it's

00:02:15.980 --> 00:02:21.100
something about, something about
humanity in that word, harvest.

00:02:21.100 --> 00:02:22.760
I think something very powerful.

00:02:22.760 --> 00:02:25.990
And many of the tribal to
urban to suburban festivals

00:02:25.990 --> 00:02:28.030
are always based on harvest.

00:02:28.030 --> 00:02:30.820
So we suggested that we
should call it harvest,

00:02:30.820 --> 00:02:33.030
as a word gratitude.

00:02:33.030 --> 00:02:35.210
So it's vegetarian because
I thought that there's

00:02:35.210 --> 00:02:36.520
such a large market now.

00:02:36.520 --> 00:02:40.120
There's so much of awareness
of vegetarian food.

00:02:40.120 --> 00:02:41.890
I wouldn't say that it's a fad.

00:02:41.890 --> 00:02:43.490
It's here to stay.

00:02:43.490 --> 00:02:44.950
And it's great.

00:02:44.950 --> 00:02:48.070
That I, being an Indian
and being an Indian chef,

00:02:48.070 --> 00:02:51.877
that vegetarian is not like some
which you are like, you know.

00:02:51.877 --> 00:02:54.335
I remember when we had eggs
for the first time in the home,

00:02:54.335 --> 00:02:55.570
we didn't eat it.

00:02:55.570 --> 00:02:57.070
Our grandmother
wouldn't let us eat.

00:02:57.070 --> 00:02:59.340
She said, think about the hens.

00:02:59.340 --> 00:03:01.470
And I'm like, really, why?

00:03:01.470 --> 00:03:04.330
You stole somebody's babies.

00:03:04.330 --> 00:03:05.880
I remember it's
like 1980 something.

00:03:05.880 --> 00:03:07.400
It's like so true in a way.

00:03:07.400 --> 00:03:10.700
But we never had, until I
was 17, I went to college.

00:03:10.700 --> 00:03:12.710
And I had, started
enjoying, and understanding

00:03:12.710 --> 00:03:13.670
seafood and everything.

00:03:13.670 --> 00:03:16.420
Because where I come from,
it's only fried fish sometimes,

00:03:16.420 --> 00:03:18.340
if you're rich, and
you've saved money

00:03:18.340 --> 00:03:20.360
on the first Sunday
of the month.

00:03:20.360 --> 00:03:23.790
But this is a
fantastic opportunity

00:03:23.790 --> 00:03:25.849
to talk about the
culture through food.

00:03:25.849 --> 00:03:27.390
AMAR JOSHI: Yeah,
there's certainly--

00:03:27.390 --> 00:03:28.806
VIKAS KHANNA:
That's what this is.

00:03:28.806 --> 00:03:31.210
AMAR JOSHI: Yeah, I think
this perception of vegetarian

00:03:31.210 --> 00:03:34.270
being like a substitute,
like especially

00:03:34.270 --> 00:03:37.310
in some Western culture,
that's like think--

00:03:37.310 --> 00:03:39.472
looks like yours go a long
way in correcting that.

00:03:39.472 --> 00:03:40.930
VIKAS KHANNA: It's
good that we can

00:03:40.930 --> 00:03:42.221
talk about something different.

00:03:42.221 --> 00:03:42.970
AMAR JOSHI: Yeah.

00:03:42.970 --> 00:03:45.261
VIKAS KHANNA: It's like not
just giving the market what

00:03:45.261 --> 00:03:47.610
they want to consume.

00:03:47.610 --> 00:03:49.650
It is also giving
something which matters,

00:03:49.650 --> 00:03:52.860
something which is essential,
and something you believe in.

00:03:52.860 --> 00:03:55.420
And there's a dedication
page-- it says it all.

00:03:55.420 --> 00:03:58.670
I'm not a vegetarian at all.

00:03:58.670 --> 00:04:00.870
I eat everything.

00:04:00.870 --> 00:04:03.280
There's a page here that says
dedicated to all my gurus,

00:04:03.280 --> 00:04:05.830
who taught me how to
cook and roll breads.

00:04:05.830 --> 00:04:08.880
And most important, they
were all vegetarian.

00:04:08.880 --> 00:04:11.460
They truly showed me the
power of food and love.

00:04:11.460 --> 00:04:14.560
So this first page itself,
is like it's for me,

00:04:14.560 --> 00:04:15.890
this is not just a book.

00:04:15.890 --> 00:04:20.630
It's a dedication to all those
wrinkled hands, what I say.

00:04:20.630 --> 00:04:24.380
Who stood by me and kept no
secret from me in the kitchen.

00:04:24.380 --> 00:04:26.510
And without even
knowing that eventually

00:04:26.510 --> 00:04:28.860
you'll be running
Junoon in New York.

00:04:28.860 --> 00:04:30.310
They did not.

00:04:30.310 --> 00:04:33.620
It's a big leap from
where I come from.

00:04:33.620 --> 00:04:35.630
AMAR JOSHI: Yeah, so
speaking of Junoon, right,

00:04:35.630 --> 00:04:39.346
congratulations on winning your
fifth Michelin star, right?

00:04:39.346 --> 00:04:40.220
Did I get that right?

00:04:40.220 --> 00:04:41.011
VIKAS KHANNA: Yeah.

00:04:41.011 --> 00:04:43.566
[APPLAUSE]

00:04:43.566 --> 00:04:47.480
AMAR JOSHI: Yeah, it's great
to be in that category, right?

00:04:49.366 --> 00:04:51.490
VIKAS KHANNA: There are
too many great restaurants,

00:04:51.490 --> 00:04:54.090
and too many great Indian
chefs in the world.

00:04:54.090 --> 00:04:56.910
I'm proud to be part
of the fraternity.

00:04:56.910 --> 00:05:00.490
AMAR JOSHI: Nice, so what does
it take to earn a Michelin star

00:05:00.490 --> 00:05:03.730
and keep it for five
years, and hopefully more?

00:05:03.730 --> 00:05:06.070
VIKAS KHANNA: It's
like-- it's something

00:05:06.070 --> 00:05:11.040
which is very strange that you
know-- In 1990, when I joined

00:05:11.040 --> 00:05:13.490
college, my principal or the
people who gave me admission,

00:05:13.490 --> 00:05:15.406
said we will give you
admission on a condition

00:05:15.406 --> 00:05:17.790
that you're going to learn
English, which I actually

00:05:17.790 --> 00:05:19.346
failed in the first semester.

00:05:19.346 --> 00:05:21.420
And I think they forgot
about that condition,

00:05:21.420 --> 00:05:22.972
and they let me
go in the college.

00:05:22.972 --> 00:05:25.430
But I read this magazine which
talked about Michelin stars.

00:05:25.430 --> 00:05:28.030
This is the first time I've
heard of a Michelin star.

00:05:28.030 --> 00:05:32.008
I had no idea about the
Michelin star also then.

00:05:32.008 --> 00:05:33.340
AMAR JOSHI: Yeah.

00:05:33.340 --> 00:05:35.610
VIKAS KHANNA: But
and the last line

00:05:35.610 --> 00:05:39.580
said that this is the glorified
kitchens of the world.

00:05:39.580 --> 00:05:41.300
Earn a Michelin
star and everything.

00:05:41.300 --> 00:05:44.030
And said unfortunately,
India, even

00:05:44.030 --> 00:05:46.510
with such large
population, love for food,

00:05:46.510 --> 00:05:49.160
a chef would not
be able to get it.

00:05:49.160 --> 00:05:52.440
And I think that was a
very powerful last line

00:05:52.440 --> 00:05:56.250
about someone telling a
child who's starting off

00:05:56.250 --> 00:06:01.120
in the industry saying that you
will be exempt from the glory.

00:06:01.120 --> 00:06:04.160
And it was like, for me
it was like a very big--

00:06:04.160 --> 00:06:06.270
that line was trapped
with me forever.

00:06:06.270 --> 00:06:09.440
I said once in my
lifetime I want to get it.

00:06:09.440 --> 00:06:10.670
And they call you.

00:06:10.670 --> 00:06:12.660
They call you in the afternoon.

00:06:12.660 --> 00:06:13.830
It's very difficult.

00:06:13.830 --> 00:06:15.960
I will not be able to
explain properly in English.

00:06:15.960 --> 00:06:18.480
If you're talking Punjabi,
I can explain right and left

00:06:18.480 --> 00:06:20.180
what I was feeling that time.

00:06:20.180 --> 00:06:22.880
So they call you around 1
o'clock in the afternoon.

00:06:22.880 --> 00:06:25.074
And I pick up the phone
and they said yes.

00:06:25.074 --> 00:06:26.490
I'm going from the
Michelin guide,

00:06:26.490 --> 00:06:30.280
we just want to-- And
I'm like, I was so numb.

00:06:30.280 --> 00:06:31.350
I didn't understand.

00:06:31.350 --> 00:06:33.300
Did I win it or
did I not win in?

00:06:33.300 --> 00:06:33.800
First time.

00:06:33.800 --> 00:06:36.450
So everybody's asking me
standing there, chef, what?

00:06:36.450 --> 00:06:38.450
I said, I didn't understand
what she was saying.

00:06:38.450 --> 00:06:42.050
I was like, did
you get it or not?

00:06:42.050 --> 00:06:45.157
But this is when the [INAUDIBLE]
was not, like you know now,

00:06:45.157 --> 00:06:46.490
you can see the list right away.

00:06:46.490 --> 00:06:48.240
But we got it.

00:06:48.240 --> 00:06:53.260
It was-- I think no one should
be exempt from experimenting

00:06:53.260 --> 00:06:54.850
with their life.

00:06:54.850 --> 00:06:57.710
AMAR JOSHI: It's nice that you
take on the challenge and--

00:06:57.710 --> 00:06:59.626
VIKAS KHANNA: That movie's
really inspired me.

00:06:59.626 --> 00:07:02.290
It's funny to talk about
a rat at this stage.

00:07:02.290 --> 00:07:04.160
But Ratatouille
really inspired me.

00:07:04.160 --> 00:07:08.010
And that line about that a great
artist can come from anywhere.

00:07:08.010 --> 00:07:09.010
AMAR JOSHI: That's true.

00:07:09.010 --> 00:07:09.980
VIKAS KHANNA: It can
come from anywhere.

00:07:09.980 --> 00:07:12.350
But I also feel that coming
from humble background,

00:07:12.350 --> 00:07:18.760
it's an amazing hunger
and you have 24 hours.

00:07:18.760 --> 00:07:21.610
And you don't take
a day for granted.

00:07:21.610 --> 00:07:24.780
Because you don't know
that this must be something

00:07:24.780 --> 00:07:26.257
which is greater than you.

00:07:26.257 --> 00:07:27.465
AMAR JOSHI: That's inspiring.

00:07:27.465 --> 00:07:29.770
Thank you.

00:07:29.770 --> 00:07:34.100
So the menu at Junoon,
right, how is that,

00:07:34.100 --> 00:07:36.080
is that like completely,
did you think

00:07:36.080 --> 00:07:38.040
about making creating a
completely Indian menu

00:07:38.040 --> 00:07:41.501
or is this like sort of get
with the Western palate and--

00:07:41.501 --> 00:07:42.625
VIKAS KHANNA: It's as pure.

00:07:45.619 --> 00:07:48.160
I think it's almost nine years--
nine or 10 years ago, when I

00:07:48.160 --> 00:07:49.430
first met Mr. Rajesh Bhardwaj.

00:07:49.430 --> 00:07:53.990
He's the, I want to say
that he is the main brain.

00:07:53.990 --> 00:07:56.730
And I happen to
be on the journey.

00:07:56.730 --> 00:07:59.610
And it's fantastic when you
first talk about Indian food.

00:07:59.610 --> 00:08:02.530
And he kept telling one
thing, which was so,

00:08:02.530 --> 00:08:04.320
it was a very
powerful message what

00:08:04.320 --> 00:08:05.680
he wanted to give the world.

00:08:05.680 --> 00:08:08.520
If you want to have a--
a fine dining restaurant

00:08:08.520 --> 00:08:13.140
which serves Indian food, not
just an Indian restaurant.

00:08:13.140 --> 00:08:16.429
We want to give an experience
that the moment you

00:08:16.429 --> 00:08:17.970
walk into a restaurant,
that you feel

00:08:17.970 --> 00:08:22.970
that this is like the gravity of
Indian culture cuisine flavors.

00:08:22.970 --> 00:08:25.530
So you have to be
pure in your flavors.

00:08:25.530 --> 00:08:27.770
But you should also be evolving.

00:08:27.770 --> 00:08:29.250
It should always be evolving.

00:08:29.250 --> 00:08:31.980
There should always be something
new in your plate every time

00:08:31.980 --> 00:08:32.770
you come in.

00:08:32.770 --> 00:08:35.030
There should always be
something new to be offered.

00:08:35.030 --> 00:08:38.309
Because that is what
New York is about.

00:08:38.309 --> 00:08:39.929
If you have to
survive here, you've

00:08:39.929 --> 00:08:43.240
got to be re-inventive
all the time.

00:08:43.240 --> 00:08:48.850
So it's cuisine which is
totally Indian on the soul.

00:08:48.850 --> 00:08:51.810
But you might feel that it has
been presented in absolutely

00:08:51.810 --> 00:08:54.932
new norms and new faces.

00:08:54.932 --> 00:08:55.640
AMAR JOSHI: Nice.

00:08:55.640 --> 00:08:58.040
Have you considered doing
some like, something

00:08:58.040 --> 00:09:02.420
like Punjabi dhaba, upscale
restaurant you know?

00:09:02.420 --> 00:09:08.610
VIKAS KHANNA: [SPEAKING PUNJABI]
Dhaba means a small kiosk.

00:09:08.610 --> 00:09:11.570
I've been running
it since I was 17.

00:09:11.570 --> 00:09:14.780
It's really interesting
that my father used to say

00:09:14.780 --> 00:09:15.860
don't call it a business.

00:09:15.860 --> 00:09:17.090
Call it a charity.

00:09:17.090 --> 00:09:19.670
Because if somebody will
come to eat our food,

00:09:19.670 --> 00:09:23.420
we'll be so happy, we'll
give them for free.

00:09:23.420 --> 00:09:25.910
And if somebody would
complain, we won't charge it.

00:09:25.910 --> 00:09:28.160
My dad would always be
like, when are you going

00:09:28.160 --> 00:09:29.290
to learn how to make money?

00:09:29.290 --> 00:09:32.340
It's like, I said you know, as
long as-- my grandmother would

00:09:32.340 --> 00:09:35.350
always stand by me and
she said, as long as he's

00:09:35.350 --> 00:09:38.060
happy in what he
does, it does not

00:09:38.060 --> 00:09:39.510
make any difference otherwise.

00:09:39.510 --> 00:09:40.630
And I love that.

00:09:40.630 --> 00:09:43.060
It stuck with me.

00:09:43.060 --> 00:09:46.880
My first job was, of course, as
an apprentice in the kitchen.

00:09:46.880 --> 00:09:52.020
But it was also, my first
business was running a dhaba.

00:09:52.020 --> 00:09:54.490
In the backside of my house,
in a very narrow lane,

00:09:54.490 --> 00:09:56.820
where only one car can come.

00:09:56.820 --> 00:09:58.880
But we did the best,
what we could do,

00:09:58.880 --> 00:10:00.990
in our ability of making
three, four dishes which

00:10:00.990 --> 00:10:02.240
I knew how to cook.

00:10:02.240 --> 00:10:04.020
That's what.

00:10:04.020 --> 00:10:06.750
And charging 22 rupees.

00:10:06.750 --> 00:10:10.390
And whatever people can really
eat, it was all you can eat.

00:10:10.390 --> 00:10:12.444
So it was always like--

00:10:12.444 --> 00:10:13.860
AMAR JOSHI: 20
rupees is 10 cent--

00:10:13.860 --> 00:10:15.568
VIKAS KHANNA: 20 rupees
is like how much?

00:10:15.568 --> 00:10:17.732
AMAR JOSHI: Yeah, it-- 40 cents.

00:10:17.732 --> 00:10:19.190
VIKAS KHANNA: 30
cents or 40 cents.

00:10:19.190 --> 00:10:20.975
So it was like
amazing that you'll

00:10:20.975 --> 00:10:23.470
have people who will
say, oh, you know what, I

00:10:23.470 --> 00:10:24.860
didn't enjoy the food so much.

00:10:24.860 --> 00:10:25.693
I couldn't eat much.

00:10:25.693 --> 00:10:27.400
And can you just
pack the rest for me?

00:10:27.400 --> 00:10:30.331
It's like, OK.

00:10:30.331 --> 00:10:32.140
But it was a great
training ground.

00:10:32.140 --> 00:10:34.870
People discount the
fact that starting small

00:10:34.870 --> 00:10:38.790
is something that--
I'm telling you,

00:10:38.790 --> 00:10:41.950
even the next glorified
Indian chef, or anyone who'll

00:10:41.950 --> 00:10:44.980
get the Michelin star, will come
from a very similar background

00:10:44.980 --> 00:10:47.790
and belief, that it was
the little things you

00:10:47.790 --> 00:10:51.190
learned while you were
doing the smallest of jobs.

00:10:51.190 --> 00:10:54.340
I still don't forget
my first [INAUDIBLE].

00:10:54.340 --> 00:10:56.720
He bought 24 plates,
white plates.

00:10:56.720 --> 00:10:58.640
We got 23 chairs.

00:10:58.640 --> 00:11:01.650
It was crazy, when we had more
than 24 people to cook for,

00:11:01.650 --> 00:11:04.310
we'll have to go back and wash
the plate, and bring it back.

00:11:04.310 --> 00:11:08.090
So I'm just waiting for
somebody to finish fast, man.

