He's looking at the publisher.

00:22:23.350 --> 00:22:28.060
VIKAS KHANNA: No, I
write what I feel.

00:22:28.060 --> 00:22:29.160
I can't be scripted.

00:22:29.160 --> 00:22:30.620
I have a very big problem.

00:22:30.620 --> 00:22:31.210
See?

00:22:31.210 --> 00:22:33.650
I was scripted that line to
talk about, even sometimes

00:22:33.650 --> 00:22:35.610
the restaurant, I've been
scripted what to say,

00:22:35.610 --> 00:22:37.720
I can't say it.

00:22:37.720 --> 00:22:40.410
It becomes very hard for me
to explain something which is

00:22:40.410 --> 00:22:42.540
organic and which is internal.

00:22:42.540 --> 00:22:43.540
It is not scripted.

00:22:43.540 --> 00:22:45.000
It can't be.

00:22:45.000 --> 00:22:46.350
AMAR JOSHI: Nice.

00:22:46.350 --> 00:22:49.890
So in the process of coming up
with the book or a new dish,

00:22:49.890 --> 00:22:52.830
right, how do you weigh
innovation versus tradition

00:22:52.830 --> 00:22:56.640
as in you know
this formula, dish,

00:22:56.640 --> 00:23:00.019
and then how do you make
it more presentable?

00:23:00.019 --> 00:23:02.185
VIKAS KHANNA: Amar, you
think I believe in formulas?

00:23:02.185 --> 00:23:03.040
AMAR JOSHI: Well, exactly.

00:23:03.040 --> 00:23:03.920
No, not formulas.

00:23:03.920 --> 00:23:06.460
But what's your
creative process like?

00:23:06.460 --> 00:23:08.976
VIKAS KHANNA: Creative
process is extremely simple.

00:23:08.976 --> 00:23:10.850
People try to make a
very big deal out of it.

00:23:10.850 --> 00:23:12.002
It is not.

00:23:12.002 --> 00:23:12.870
It is not.

00:23:12.870 --> 00:23:14.917
It's just food.

00:23:14.917 --> 00:23:17.250
And you know, I said something
which was like little bit

00:23:17.250 --> 00:23:20.840
off-- should be off
the records actually.

00:23:20.840 --> 00:23:23.247
It's like when
people having dinner,

00:23:23.247 --> 00:23:25.330
and said this is one of
the best meals of my life,

00:23:25.330 --> 00:23:26.900
people tell you at Junoon.

00:23:26.900 --> 00:23:32.870
So I always interrupt and
say that food doesn't matter.

00:23:32.870 --> 00:23:33.790
Food doesn't matter.

00:23:33.790 --> 00:23:36.970
It's the people you're
having dinner with.

00:23:36.970 --> 00:23:38.700
AMAR JOSHI: That's true.

00:23:38.700 --> 00:23:43.440
VIKAS KHANNA: Well,
it was off the record.

00:23:43.440 --> 00:23:48.170
But it's like really, like
how much work goes into it?

00:23:48.170 --> 00:23:49.800
We adjust the backdrop.

00:23:49.800 --> 00:23:51.510
We adjust the furniture.

00:23:51.510 --> 00:23:53.010
And I'm not talking
about the chair.

00:23:53.010 --> 00:23:54.480
I'm talking about you.

00:23:54.480 --> 00:23:55.700
The food is the backdrop.

00:23:55.700 --> 00:23:56.720
It's the people.

00:23:56.720 --> 00:23:58.290
It's that energy.

00:23:58.290 --> 00:24:00.060
It's that moment.

00:24:00.060 --> 00:24:02.460
Restaurants will come,
and restaurants will go.

00:24:02.460 --> 00:24:04.734
It's such a transient world.

00:24:04.734 --> 00:24:06.150
There was something
before Junoon.

00:24:06.150 --> 00:24:08.640
There's something after Junoon.

00:24:08.640 --> 00:24:10.677
That's the true.

00:24:10.677 --> 00:24:12.010
I'm a big follow the Dalai Lama.

00:24:12.010 --> 00:24:13.230
That's why I say that.

00:24:13.230 --> 00:24:17.230
But it's that moment that you
spend there in that restaurant

00:24:17.230 --> 00:24:19.410
and said, do you
remember my 21st birthday

00:24:19.410 --> 00:24:22.180
when the chef actually
got the cake out?

00:24:22.180 --> 00:24:24.649
Do you remember that moment
when we had that dinner?

00:24:24.649 --> 00:24:25.190
You remember?

00:24:25.190 --> 00:24:26.620
Oh my god, I miss
my grandmother.

00:24:26.620 --> 00:24:29.460
You remember the last
meal we had with her?

00:24:29.460 --> 00:24:31.390
It was at Junoon.

00:24:31.390 --> 00:24:36.040
My publisher, because of
whom this book is there.

00:24:36.040 --> 00:24:40.104
Mr.-- talk or something.

00:24:40.104 --> 00:24:41.020
AMAR JOSHI: All right.

00:24:41.020 --> 00:24:43.700
So you mentioned the
Dalai Lama, right?

00:24:43.700 --> 00:24:46.115
You wrote a book about
him on his 80th birthday.

00:24:46.115 --> 00:24:46.906
VIKAS KHANNA: Yeah.

00:24:46.906 --> 00:24:47.270
AMAR JOSHI: Yeah.

00:24:47.270 --> 00:24:48.280
What was it called?

00:24:48.280 --> 00:24:49.060
"Timeless Legacy."

00:24:49.060 --> 00:24:49.580
VIKAS KHANNA: Oh my god!

00:24:49.580 --> 00:24:51.210
It was such an
amazing experience.

00:24:51.210 --> 00:24:53.246
I made a cake for him.

00:24:53.246 --> 00:24:54.620
I'm not going to
get too excited.

00:24:54.620 --> 00:24:55.703
I want to say it normally.

00:24:55.703 --> 00:24:57.755
I made a cake for him
from his native breads

00:24:57.755 --> 00:24:58.820
from his hometown.

00:24:58.820 --> 00:25:00.290
I lived in Tibet.

00:25:00.290 --> 00:25:04.210
So I can make like almost
16 different breads

00:25:04.210 --> 00:25:05.440
of Tibetan culture.

00:25:05.440 --> 00:25:06.800
Totally different.

00:25:06.800 --> 00:25:08.660
So I made this bread,
I made it very thin.

00:25:08.660 --> 00:25:10.560
And I made like layers of cake.

00:25:10.560 --> 00:25:13.870
So I wanted to get 80
layers in that one cake.

00:25:13.870 --> 00:25:15.320
So 80 years.

00:25:15.320 --> 00:25:18.360
I couldn't do that because it
was becoming like this big.

00:25:18.360 --> 00:25:20.820
I'm wondering how
he's going cut it now.

00:25:20.820 --> 00:25:24.540
So I made only like,
almost like 14 layers.

00:25:24.540 --> 00:25:26.410
So and I take it to him.

00:25:26.410 --> 00:25:28.220
You'd be surprising
when you hear this.

00:25:28.220 --> 00:25:30.590
So I put 80 candles on him
and I said his holiness,

00:25:30.590 --> 00:25:33.587
it's your 80th birthday,
and I want you to cut that.

00:25:33.587 --> 00:25:35.920
So I'm sitting there and I'm
waiting like him, that he's

00:25:35.920 --> 00:25:37.250
going to blow the candles.

00:25:37.250 --> 00:25:41.400
So I said, and you don't
instruct people of that status,

00:25:41.400 --> 00:25:43.290
that blow the candles!

00:25:43.290 --> 00:25:44.280
Make a wish.

00:25:44.280 --> 00:25:46.930
So and he's there.

00:25:46.930 --> 00:25:49.570
And it's one of the
very powerful moments.

00:25:49.570 --> 00:25:51.990
So candles are burning, and
he starts taking the candles,

00:25:51.990 --> 00:25:54.026
and starts putting
them on the side.

00:25:54.026 --> 00:25:55.980
So I'm like, I
just looked at him.

00:25:55.980 --> 00:25:58.330
I said, did you make a wish?

00:25:58.330 --> 00:26:02.220
He's saying, in my culture,
you don't cut somebody's life

00:26:02.220 --> 00:26:05.410
off to wish for a longer life.

00:26:05.410 --> 00:26:08.470
I can't cut the
life of this candle

00:26:08.470 --> 00:26:11.580
so that I can wish
for my long life.

00:26:11.580 --> 00:26:12.830
I thought--

00:26:12.830 --> 00:26:13.630
[SPEAKING PUNJABI]

00:26:17.680 --> 00:26:19.940
Sorry, how did he
think about this?

00:26:19.940 --> 00:26:22.580
I would have never even
would've cared that you just

00:26:22.580 --> 00:26:23.940
cut the life of that candle.

00:26:23.940 --> 00:26:25.290
It was amazing.

00:26:25.290 --> 00:26:30.320
And what was the greatest
part was on social media,

00:26:30.320 --> 00:26:32.150
I post a lot of stuff every day.

00:26:32.150 --> 00:26:33.180
Wrong English.

00:26:33.180 --> 00:26:34.646
I put something.

00:26:34.646 --> 00:26:36.020
AMAR JOSHI: Yeah,
just a plug in.

00:26:36.020 --> 00:26:38.020
You should all follow
him on social media.

00:26:38.020 --> 00:26:38.960
He's great.

00:26:38.960 --> 00:26:41.472
[SPEAKING PUNJABI]

00:26:41.472 --> 00:26:42.930
VIKAS KHANNA: I'm
not promoting it.

00:26:42.930 --> 00:26:44.980
But then I'll have
somebody, JR or somebody

00:26:44.980 --> 00:26:47.850
is like you should consult
with us or when you write,

00:26:47.850 --> 00:26:50.280
it's totally wrong English.

00:26:50.280 --> 00:26:52.150
And then say, OK,
people liked it.

00:26:52.150 --> 00:26:53.980
For what?

00:26:53.980 --> 00:26:55.480
So I put it on
social media that I'm

00:26:55.480 --> 00:26:57.230
meeting his holiness
on his 80th birthday,

00:26:57.230 --> 00:26:59.710
and I want you to ask
any questions to him.

00:26:59.710 --> 00:27:02.650
So there's going
to be 80 questions.

00:27:02.650 --> 00:27:05.000
You would be amazed by the
amount of questions we got.

00:27:05.000 --> 00:27:09.000
And my favorite question
was, do you ever wear jeans?

00:27:09.000 --> 00:27:11.420
A little kid asked from school.

00:27:11.420 --> 00:27:16.300
And American kids can be so--
they can think so openly.

00:27:16.300 --> 00:27:17.630
It's amazing.

00:27:17.630 --> 00:27:19.330
And he asked do you
ever wear jeans?

00:27:19.330 --> 00:27:21.590
So I asked his holiness,
the first question was

00:27:21.590 --> 00:27:23.320
do you have a driver's license?

00:27:23.320 --> 00:27:24.020
And he says no.

00:27:24.020 --> 00:27:26.240
I says me too.

00:27:26.240 --> 00:27:29.080
I didn't know how react to that.

00:27:29.080 --> 00:27:31.120
And then I asked him,
do you ever wear jeans?

00:27:31.120 --> 00:27:34.740
He says that, and
he just kept quiet.

00:27:34.740 --> 00:27:38.430
I said is the yes or is that no,
because I'm writing it kind of.

00:27:38.430 --> 00:27:42.190
I was behaving like an
Oprah moment for my life.

00:27:42.190 --> 00:27:45.370
And he said that I
would pants one time.

00:27:45.370 --> 00:27:48.190
And he had to leave Tibet.

00:27:48.190 --> 00:27:50.800
They had to-- he
had to disguise.

00:27:50.800 --> 00:27:54.010
And he said that when I
reached the Indian borders,

00:27:54.010 --> 00:27:58.120
he said there was a Sikh
guy who was standing there.

00:27:58.120 --> 00:27:59.510
And I was getting a pant.

00:27:59.510 --> 00:28:01.360
That's all I remember.

00:28:01.360 --> 00:28:04.314
And I left my country.

00:28:04.314 --> 00:28:09.240
I'm like, oh my god,
this man is brilliant.

00:28:09.240 --> 00:28:11.700
And I love him, not because
he say about religion.

00:28:11.700 --> 00:28:13.950
He talks about something,
that you don't need religion

00:28:13.950 --> 00:28:14.980
if you educate them.

00:28:14.980 --> 00:28:17.850
And I love that.

00:28:17.850 --> 00:28:21.567
He's such-- and he
loves scientists.

00:28:21.567 --> 00:28:23.650
More than anything else,
he says I love scientists

00:28:23.650 --> 00:28:25.010
because they give you facts.

00:28:25.010 --> 00:28:26.402
They don't misguide you.

00:28:26.402 --> 00:28:27.860
They're trying to
find the research

00:28:27.860 --> 00:28:29.600
of the true cycle of nature.

00:28:29.600 --> 00:28:30.960
And I'm like, I'm your big fan.

00:28:30.960 --> 00:28:31.970
Can I tell you that?

00:28:31.970 --> 00:28:33.870
But I was really star
struck talking to him.

00:28:33.870 --> 00:28:35.370
And he didn't
understand my English.

00:28:35.370 --> 00:28:37.320
Neither did I
understand his English.

00:28:37.320 --> 00:28:39.746
So it was OK.

00:28:39.746 --> 00:28:41.995
AMAR JOSHI: Yeah, some say
he's like an eight-year-old

00:28:41.995 --> 00:28:43.510
in an 80-year-old body.

00:28:43.510 --> 00:28:46.940
VIKAS KHANNA: He is beautiful.

00:28:46.940 --> 00:28:48.980
And there was once
intense, I asked him about,

00:28:48.980 --> 00:28:52.870
was that, about mother.

00:28:52.870 --> 00:28:56.690
And it is like, and
the photographer, I

00:28:56.690 --> 00:29:00.042
told him don't click picture at
this time, because both of us

00:29:00.042 --> 00:29:01.500
were almost on the
verge of crying.

00:29:01.500 --> 00:29:05.460
And he's saying that's
from where the child gets

00:29:05.460 --> 00:29:07.680
the compassion from.

00:29:07.680 --> 00:29:10.460
That's as sacred as the soil.

00:29:10.460 --> 00:29:12.270
And here it is.

00:29:12.270 --> 00:29:13.980
AMAR JOSHI: That's beautiful.

00:29:13.980 --> 00:29:15.982
So your mother,
your grandmother,

00:29:15.982 --> 00:29:18.440
you've mentioned that they are
big influences in your life,

00:29:18.440 --> 00:29:18.940
right?

00:29:18.940 --> 00:29:20.850
Did you learn cooking
from your grandmother?

00:29:20.850 --> 00:29:23.730
How was it, like
growing up in India?

00:29:23.730 --> 00:29:25.770
Did you have a
garden or a house?

00:29:25.770 --> 00:29:27.186
VIKAS KHANNA: We
had a small piece

00:29:27.186 --> 00:29:30.060
of-- back of the house,
a small strip of soil,

00:29:30.060 --> 00:29:32.620
in which I would try
to think that I'm going

00:29:32.620 --> 00:29:34.520
to be a farmer when I grow up.

00:29:34.520 --> 00:29:36.160
So I'll try to grow
everything there.

00:29:36.160 --> 00:29:38.300
And we had a small
container, a brass container.

00:29:38.300 --> 00:29:41.740
A lot of Indians of my
generation will relate to that.

00:29:41.740 --> 00:29:44.190
You people are three, four
generations younger than me.

00:29:44.190 --> 00:29:47.880
But it was a small
container of cardamom.

00:29:47.880 --> 00:29:49.640
And I loved cardamom.

00:29:49.640 --> 00:29:52.600
But cardamom will
not be used in food.

00:29:52.600 --> 00:29:54.780
I know that's a
very strong comment.

00:29:54.780 --> 00:29:56.840
Because it was very expensive.

00:29:56.840 --> 00:29:59.620
So only when the son-in-law
will be coming home,

00:29:59.620 --> 00:30:02.390
the rice pudding will be
made with one cardamom.

00:30:02.390 --> 00:30:06.080
And somehow it just
lands up on his bowl.

00:30:06.080 --> 00:30:07.740
Right on top of his bowl.

00:30:07.740 --> 00:30:09.380
And I'm like waiting for him.

00:30:09.380 --> 00:30:11.720
I said, and didn't
care about cardamom.

00:30:11.720 --> 00:30:13.280
And I'm the one
who's watching it.

00:30:13.280 --> 00:30:15.580
So I'll try to steal it
after they're finished.

00:30:15.580 --> 00:30:18.410
And I'll try to go
and sew in the soil,

00:30:18.410 --> 00:30:21.000
in the back of my garden,
expecting that one day,

00:30:21.000 --> 00:30:22.670
I'm going to have
a cardamom tree.

00:30:22.670 --> 00:30:26.400
See, we were born in
non-google, again Google office,

00:30:26.400 --> 00:30:27.880
we were born in
non-google world.

00:30:27.880 --> 00:30:30.420
So we didn't know how
cardamom plant looked like.

00:30:30.420 --> 00:30:33.060
Now you can ask Google anything.

00:30:33.060 --> 00:30:34.810
Back then I didn't
know how cardamom grew,

00:30:34.810 --> 00:30:35.790
and how it happened.

00:30:35.790 --> 00:30:37.560
So I write a story
here in this book.

00:30:37.560 --> 00:30:39.590
It says will cardamom grow?

00:30:39.590 --> 00:30:41.680
And it is the honest
truth about nature.

00:30:41.680 --> 00:30:45.410
Is that it says that
will cardamom grow?

00:30:45.410 --> 00:30:47.506
And I write about
that it never grew.

00:30:47.506 --> 00:30:49.130
I would come, back
running from school,

00:30:49.130 --> 00:30:51.200
searching that I would
have a cardamom plant.

00:30:51.200 --> 00:30:52.150
It never grew.

00:30:52.150 --> 00:30:54.500
So my garden was
as failure as me.

00:30:54.500 --> 00:30:57.109
Nothing grew there.

00:30:57.109 --> 00:30:59.150
AMAR JOSHI: I bet a lot
of people would disagree.

00:30:59.150 --> 00:31:00.070
VIKAS KHANNA: But
I would pretend.

00:31:00.070 --> 00:31:01.250
We had a tomatoes one time.

00:31:01.250 --> 00:31:01.890
I'll never forget.

00:31:01.890 --> 00:31:04.264
We had a tomato, and we got
so excited, me and my sister,

00:31:04.264 --> 00:31:06.180
we kept touching it
and it fell down.

00:31:06.180 --> 00:31:09.214
So it actually never grew.

00:31:09.214 --> 00:31:10.380
AMAR JOSHI: Your excitement.

00:31:10.380 --> 00:31:12.080
VIKAS KHANNA: It's like the
homemade ice cream, you know?

00:31:12.080 --> 00:31:13.664
Homemade ice cream
never freezes.

00:31:13.664 --> 00:31:15.580
Because every child wants
to go in the freezer

00:31:15.580 --> 00:31:16.970
and check if it's ready.

00:31:16.970 --> 00:31:19.410
So eventually you
get to drink that.

00:31:19.410 --> 00:31:23.280
It's like same thing
when people like us

00:31:23.280 --> 00:31:24.280
when you try to farming.

00:31:24.280 --> 00:31:26.110
And we have one crop coming out.

00:31:26.110 --> 00:31:28.720
We all touching that crop
all the time that it dies.

00:31:28.720 --> 00:31:32.490
It's like, guys, leave me alone.

00:31:32.490 --> 00:31:34.350
AMAR JOSHI: Nice.

00:31:34.350 --> 00:31:37.760
So tell us something
about how you started off

00:31:37.760 --> 00:31:42.710
as-- before Junoon, your
career as a restauranter.

00:31:42.710 --> 00:31:44.640
Things that worked out,
things that did not,

00:31:44.640 --> 00:31:46.135
I find those things
very inspiring.

00:31:46.135 --> 00:31:47.640
You have a great story.

00:31:47.640 --> 00:31:50.710
VIKAS KHANNA: I'm
still work in progress.

00:31:50.710 --> 00:31:53.009
I think it's OK.

00:31:53.009 --> 00:31:54.550
This country was
based on resilience.

00:31:56.924 --> 00:31:58.340
This country teaches
you something

00:31:58.340 --> 00:32:01.990
which is called not giving up.

00:32:01.990 --> 00:32:04.190
And failing is OK.

00:32:04.190 --> 00:32:05.442
Not a big deal.

00:32:05.442 --> 00:32:06.775
I've been a failure all my life.

00:32:06.775 --> 00:32:09.010
So It's like it didn't
even affect me when

00:32:09.010 --> 00:32:10.400
we used to close a restaurant.

00:32:10.400 --> 00:32:12.570
It's like OK.

00:32:12.570 --> 00:32:14.410
But one thing would
always hurt you,

00:32:14.410 --> 00:32:19.510
that little thing back
when somebody told you

00:32:19.510 --> 00:32:21.930
that you can't do it.

00:32:21.930 --> 00:32:26.030
You somehow felt that
you lost yourself.

00:32:26.030 --> 00:32:29.300
That's a big defeat.

00:32:29.300 --> 00:32:32.000
And one day, we kept working.

00:32:32.000 --> 00:32:34.850
I was working in this restaurant
called Spice Root at the Loot

00:32:34.850 --> 00:32:37.010
Palace on Fulton Street.

00:32:37.010 --> 00:32:39.940
I get a call from the
producer, Gordon Ramsay.

00:32:39.940 --> 00:32:41.790
And they said we
want you on the show.

00:32:41.790 --> 00:32:43.920
And I go there.

00:32:43.920 --> 00:32:46.500
And it was an
amazing experience.

00:32:46.500 --> 00:32:49.200
Everything I spoke in English
was translated in English.

00:32:53.989 --> 00:32:56.030
It's like, great, what
language were you talking?

00:32:56.030 --> 00:32:59.890
I said, I was also
trying to speak English.

00:32:59.890 --> 00:33:02.790
So I said, we are in
the middle of Manhattan.

00:33:02.790 --> 00:33:03.930
And we can do it here.

00:33:03.930 --> 00:33:06.490
And it was written, V are
in the middle of Manhattan.

00:33:06.490 --> 00:33:08.540
V can do it here.

00:33:08.540 --> 00:33:11.050
So I'm like, oh god,
this is amazing.

00:33:11.050 --> 00:33:13.359
I told my dad I did a
show with Gordon Ramsey.

00:33:13.359 --> 00:33:14.650
And he says, he speaks Punjabi?

00:33:14.650 --> 00:33:16.830
And I was like, no, I
did the show in English.

00:33:16.830 --> 00:33:18.510
He said, you can speak English?

00:33:18.510 --> 00:33:21.520
I was like, kind of.

00:33:21.520 --> 00:33:24.000
I'm working very hard to learn.

00:33:24.000 --> 00:33:28.210
But later you realize that
communication, failure,

00:33:28.210 --> 00:33:31.540
everything is not important.

00:33:31.540 --> 00:33:33.990
It's a matter of heart.

00:33:33.990 --> 00:33:38.810
I'm starting a very good museum
in India, about Indian dishes

00:33:38.810 --> 00:33:40.330
and utensils and how you know?

00:33:40.330 --> 00:33:42.870
Because India has everything,
from the Portuguese,

00:33:42.870 --> 00:33:48.002
to Dutch, to French, to Mongols,
to native Indian, intertribal.

00:33:48.002 --> 00:33:48.960
There's so many dishes.

00:33:48.960 --> 00:33:52.000
So much of India is infinity.

00:33:52.000 --> 00:33:59.440
So last week, there was a
big shipment of my plates.

00:33:59.440 --> 00:34:01.600
I'm obsessed.

00:34:01.600 --> 00:34:03.565
Junoon is the right name.

00:34:03.565 --> 00:34:04.940
AMAR JOSHI: You
got to have that.

00:34:04.940 --> 00:34:06.773
VIKAS KHANNA: It's like
so many plates which

00:34:06.773 --> 00:34:09.820
been to the college where
we are doing this museum,

00:34:09.820 --> 00:34:11.590
they all broke.

00:34:11.590 --> 00:34:12.940
All these plates.

00:34:12.940 --> 00:34:15.179
Hundreds of years old plates.

00:34:15.179 --> 00:34:17.260
Everything crushed.

00:34:17.260 --> 00:34:20.520
So I called Rajesh in the middle
of the night, freaking out,

00:34:20.520 --> 00:34:21.371
all the plates.

00:34:21.371 --> 00:34:23.870
And he's like, well, did you
take insurance on the delivery?

00:34:23.870 --> 00:34:28.020
I said, no, I didn't
ask for that thing.

00:34:28.020 --> 00:34:31.290
So later I realize, and
hung up the phone with him,

00:34:31.290 --> 00:34:33.280
I totally was in a
fit for some time.

00:34:33.280 --> 00:34:36.070
It was like I give a piece
of my life to something

00:34:36.070 --> 00:34:37.425
and it just crashed.

00:34:37.425 --> 00:34:41.340
And nobody would witness that
piece of history, what I had.

00:34:41.340 --> 00:34:44.284
Had painted work
and amazing, one

00:34:44.284 --> 00:34:46.080
of the first plates
which must be literally

00:34:46.080 --> 00:34:49.130
created in India by some of
the immigrants and everything.

00:34:49.130 --> 00:34:50.050
The Jewish plates.

00:34:50.050 --> 00:34:52.449
And we had a plate, a
Passover plate I had,

00:34:52.449 --> 00:34:55.760
which is one of the
oldest Passover plate.

00:34:55.760 --> 00:34:57.730
India has the
oldest living Jews.

00:34:57.730 --> 00:35:00.730
They were one of the
first immigrants to India.

00:35:00.730 --> 00:35:03.270
Their plates, everybody who
trusted me with their heritage

00:35:03.270 --> 00:35:05.100
and gave it to me, I broke.

00:35:05.100 --> 00:35:06.790
Later I wrote a message
to my principal,

00:35:06.790 --> 00:35:09.350
saying that they
were just plates.

00:35:09.350 --> 00:35:12.030
Life is actually
the matter of heart,

00:35:12.030 --> 00:35:14.486
as long as the
heart doesn't break.

00:35:14.486 --> 00:35:20.040
So even if you feel, it's OK, as
long your heart doesn't break.

00:35:20.040 --> 00:35:21.810
Breaking of the
heart is a big deal.

00:35:21.810 --> 00:35:26.810
I'm not saying it as a chef,
or an emotional Indian,

00:35:26.810 --> 00:35:28.610
I'm seeing it as
an honest person

00:35:28.610 --> 00:35:33.610
who says that sometimes it's
that unbroken heart which

00:35:33.610 --> 00:35:35.900
makes you go on and on.

00:35:35.900 --> 00:35:36.900
And you don't see night.

00:35:36.900 --> 00:35:38.500
You don't see 24 hours.

00:35:38.500 --> 00:35:39.520
My watch doesn't work.

00:35:39.520 --> 00:35:41.190
A lot of people know that.

00:35:41.190 --> 00:35:44.235
To work with me,
it's always 12:15.

00:35:44.235 --> 00:35:45.680
It's always 12:15.

00:35:45.680 --> 00:35:48.120
That's the time I
landed in New York.

00:35:48.120 --> 00:35:51.242
It's a matter of heart.

00:35:51.242 --> 00:35:52.960
AMAR JOSHI: Wow, thank you.

00:35:52.960 --> 00:35:55.180
Very inspiring.

00:35:55.180 --> 00:35:57.190
VIKAS KHANNA: Feeling is good.

00:35:57.190 --> 00:35:59.410
Poverty teaches you a lot.

00:35:59.410 --> 00:36:02.610
There's nothing more which
you are taught in colleges

00:36:02.610 --> 00:36:04.877
and everything than poverty.

00:36:04.877 --> 00:36:06.460
Poverty turned me
into a photographer.

00:36:06.460 --> 00:36:08.460
I took most of the
pictures myself.

00:36:08.460 --> 00:36:11.280
Because it was so expensive
to get photographers on board,

00:36:11.280 --> 00:36:12.620
and to be cooking at their pace.

00:36:12.620 --> 00:36:15.274
And they're like, man,
we are getting late.

00:36:15.274 --> 00:36:16.690
Eight hours are
going to get over.

00:36:16.690 --> 00:36:17.970
The food is not ready.

00:36:17.970 --> 00:36:20.770
And you could rush the
food and the food burnt,

00:36:20.770 --> 00:36:22.270
so you learned how
to take pictures.

00:36:22.270 --> 00:36:23.744
But that extended forward.

00:36:23.744 --> 00:36:24.910
You couldn't afford editors.

00:36:24.910 --> 00:36:26.500
You started writing yourself.

00:36:26.500 --> 00:36:29.760
And then you met somebody so
fantastic like [INAUDIBLE]

00:36:29.760 --> 00:36:33.220
from Lake [INAUDIBLE] that
everybody can write English.

00:36:33.220 --> 00:36:35.770
But not everybody
can tell a story.

00:36:35.770 --> 00:36:40.530
So it's all good, as long
as the heart doesn't break.

00:36:40.530 --> 00:36:42.396
AMAR JOSHI: Nice.

00:36:42.396 --> 00:36:43.440
All right, next question.

00:36:43.440 --> 00:36:45.595
I don't know how to
follow up on that.

00:36:45.595 --> 00:36:47.470
VIKAS KHANNA: See, I
have remembered answers.

00:36:47.470 --> 00:36:49.150
Of whatever question
you ask, doesn't matter.

00:36:49.150 --> 00:36:50.910
I'm going to give the
answer what I remember.

00:36:50.910 --> 00:36:51.743
What I've memorized.

00:36:55.650 --> 00:36:57.720
AMAR JOSHI: You worked
with Gordon Ramsey.

00:36:57.720 --> 00:37:00.580
You've been on Martha
Stewart, Bobby Flay,

00:37:00.580 --> 00:37:03.830
and now you're a judge on
"Master Chef India," right?

00:37:03.830 --> 00:37:05.495
VIKAS KHANNA: I
was many shows ago.

00:37:05.495 --> 00:37:07.230
AMAR JOSHI: Yeah, so
and also one more--

00:37:07.230 --> 00:37:07.990
VIKAS KHANNA: "Twist of Taste."

00:37:07.990 --> 00:37:09.198
AMAR JOSHI: "Twist of Taste."

00:37:09.198 --> 00:37:13.260
So how does that TV
experience, the glamour life?

00:37:13.260 --> 00:37:14.900
VIKAS KHANNA: Oh,
TV's very funny.

00:37:14.900 --> 00:37:16.860
TV's really funny.

00:37:16.860 --> 00:37:20.270
TV doesn't-- TV
has its own brain.

00:37:20.270 --> 00:37:22.180
Camera has its own brain.

00:37:22.180 --> 00:37:24.780
So when I go for the first time
for audition of "Master Chef

00:37:24.780 --> 00:37:28.580
India," they were like, is he
really coming from America?

00:37:28.580 --> 00:37:30.100
He doesn't have an accent.

00:37:30.100 --> 00:37:32.430
We thought he'd be.

00:37:32.430 --> 00:37:35.340
And my Hindi's also
not real Hindi.

00:37:35.340 --> 00:37:36.689
It's Punjabi.

00:37:36.689 --> 00:37:37.980
And I think I'm speaking Hindi.

00:37:37.980 --> 00:37:40.810
And this happens to
everybody in my family.

00:37:40.810 --> 00:37:46.740
So and it was funny that you had
to really work very hard, very

00:37:46.740 --> 00:37:49.710
hard to make sure
what you're trying

00:37:49.710 --> 00:37:53.557
to explain within that duration
of time, that you explained.

00:37:53.557 --> 00:37:56.140
So many times I'll get excited,
I wouldn't be able to explain.

00:37:56.140 --> 00:37:57.780
And my director will,
OK we take a retake.

00:37:57.780 --> 00:37:58.280
It's OK.

00:37:58.280 --> 00:37:59.660
Don't get too excited.

00:37:59.660 --> 00:38:03.440
So TV is fantastic, because
TV gives you retakes.

00:38:03.440 --> 00:38:06.636
Sometimes life doesn't
give you retakes.

00:38:06.636 --> 00:38:07.510
TV gives you retakes.

00:38:07.510 --> 00:38:09.350
And one thing which
I hate about time

00:38:09.350 --> 00:38:15.790
is that sometimes doing
big projects it's very sad.

00:38:15.790 --> 00:38:18.550
TV for me, "Master Chef"
for me, is not just a show.

00:38:18.550 --> 00:38:21.250
It's something which is
very much bigger than that.

00:38:21.250 --> 00:38:22.930
People, I can't even explain it.

00:38:22.930 --> 00:38:25.300
It's like for me home coming.

00:38:25.300 --> 00:38:26.400
Homecoming is big.

00:38:26.400 --> 00:38:29.291
It could be for birds or
animals or humans or anyone.

00:38:29.291 --> 00:38:31.040
I lived in America for
almost eight years,

00:38:31.040 --> 00:38:33.990
and I get this opportunity
to step back to my country.

00:38:33.990 --> 00:38:36.180
And not that I was
doing well there.

00:38:36.180 --> 00:38:41.504
I couldn't deliver what they
wanted, and I left the show.

00:38:41.504 --> 00:38:43.920
And I told my mom, I called
her around 11:30 in the night.

00:38:43.920 --> 00:38:45.660
I said, mom, I'm
going back to America.

00:38:45.660 --> 00:38:47.118
This is never going
to look for me.

00:38:47.118 --> 00:38:50.700
She says, you know, this is the
first time your homeland has

00:38:50.700 --> 00:38:53.240
asked you for something.

00:38:53.240 --> 00:38:55.860
There are a lot of kids who
are waiting to hear your story.

00:38:55.860 --> 00:38:57.541
Don't give up.

00:38:57.541 --> 00:38:59.500
I said, OK, that's
all I wanted to hear.

00:38:59.500 --> 00:39:01.687
I told the driver,
get back to the hotel.

00:39:01.687 --> 00:39:02.770
So I go back to the hotel.

00:39:02.770 --> 00:39:05.290
I practice a lot,
what I have to do.

00:39:05.290 --> 00:39:09.174
Whatever I have to speak to
be clear in small sentences.

00:39:09.174 --> 00:39:10.840
That's a problem from
where I come from.

00:39:10.840 --> 00:39:12.350
My sentences are too long.

00:39:12.350 --> 00:39:15.460
And there's no
comments and stuff.

00:39:15.460 --> 00:39:17.300
AMAR JOSHI: Right.

00:39:17.300 --> 00:39:19.980
VIKAS KHANNA: So TV's amazing.

00:39:19.980 --> 00:39:21.230
TVs a culture.

00:39:21.230 --> 00:39:22.920
TVs like a religion.

00:39:22.920 --> 00:39:24.860
TV has an impact.

00:39:24.860 --> 00:39:27.140
TV can inspire you.

00:39:27.140 --> 00:39:31.720
TV can do a lot of stuff
to your next generation,

00:39:31.720 --> 00:39:33.820
to that next generation
of Michelin star chefs,

00:39:33.820 --> 00:39:37.950
who are getting ready in small
villages and small towns,

00:39:37.950 --> 00:39:42.570
small kitchens, smart homes,
without any resources,

00:39:42.570 --> 00:39:45.600
TV gives them hope.

00:39:45.600 --> 00:39:46.350
AMAR JOSHI: I see.

00:39:46.350 --> 00:39:48.040
They can see your story.

00:39:48.040 --> 00:39:49.300
VIKAS KHANNA: TV.

00:39:49.300 --> 00:39:54.226
They're all getting ready
to hold the next flag.

00:39:54.226 --> 00:39:55.650
AMAR JOSHI: Cool.

00:39:55.650 --> 00:39:58.570
So we have mics around the
room for audience questions,

00:39:58.570 --> 00:40:04.360
if you want tips on
cooking or something.

00:40:04.360 --> 00:40:05.954
Ask away.

00:40:05.954 --> 00:40:06.620
AUDIENCE: Hello.

00:40:06.620 --> 00:40:07.430
VIKAS KHANNA: Hi, how are you?

00:40:07.430 --> 00:40:07.730
AUDIENCE: Good.

00:40:07.730 --> 00:40:09.360
Good, thank you so
much for being here.

00:40:09.360 --> 00:40:11.880
VIKAS KHANNA: Pleasure.

00:40:11.880 --> 00:40:13.580
AUDIENCE: So I
have a friend who's

00:40:13.580 --> 00:40:17.770
trying to teach me how to
cook various Indian dishes

00:40:17.770 --> 00:40:20.100
because her daughter isn't
interested in learning

00:40:20.100 --> 00:40:21.190
how to cook.

00:40:21.190 --> 00:40:23.610
So I'm like her surrogate
daughter for that.

00:40:23.610 --> 00:40:27.350
And I'm having a really
hard time because she

00:40:27.350 --> 00:40:28.990
doesn't measure anything.

00:40:28.990 --> 00:40:31.010
She's just like, you just
know when it's right.

00:40:31.010 --> 00:40:32.176
When it's right, it's right.

00:40:32.176 --> 00:40:35.380
So what tips would
you give someone?

00:40:35.380 --> 00:40:38.830
VIKAS KHANNA: My grandmother
would say that if you measure,

00:40:38.830 --> 00:40:40.820
[SPEAKING PUNJABI] what
is barker in English?

00:40:40.820 --> 00:40:41.420
Anybody knows Hindi?

00:40:41.420 --> 00:40:42.320
AUDIENCE: Prosperity.

00:40:42.320 --> 00:40:43.361
VIKAS KHANNA: Prosperity.

00:40:43.361 --> 00:40:47.570
If you measure, it reduces
the prosperity of that dish.

00:40:47.570 --> 00:40:48.690
So she would not measure.

00:40:48.690 --> 00:40:50.150
She would think it's infinity.

00:40:50.150 --> 00:40:51.250
What?

00:40:51.250 --> 00:40:55.460
Infinity salt, can I
put that in a book?

00:40:55.460 --> 00:40:57.360
You need to have infinity oil.

00:40:57.360 --> 00:41:00.330
OK, that's a very big
problem, I know that.

00:41:00.330 --> 00:41:03.890
But the problem is that their
cooking is always consistent.

00:41:03.890 --> 00:41:06.935
And we are always measuring
and still not consistent.

00:41:06.935 --> 00:41:09.060
AUDIENCE: Mine just, it
doesn't come out like hers.

00:41:09.060 --> 00:41:10.380
VIKAS KHANNA: You got
to remember two things.

00:41:10.380 --> 00:41:11.385
Whole spices first.

00:41:11.385 --> 00:41:12.110
AUDIENCE: OK.

00:41:12.110 --> 00:41:13.526
VIKAS KHANNA:
Ground spices later.

00:41:13.526 --> 00:41:14.079
AUDIENCE: OK.

00:41:14.079 --> 00:41:15.620
VIKAS KHANNA: A lot
of Americans whom

00:41:15.620 --> 00:41:18.432
I teach Indian food,
when you're heating oil,

00:41:18.432 --> 00:41:19.890
you've got to put
the whole spices.

00:41:19.890 --> 00:41:21.556
That is how the base
of the cuisine are.

00:41:21.556 --> 00:41:23.940
You're actually what you're
doing, scientifically,

00:41:23.940 --> 00:41:27.071
you are, again this
has been memorized.

00:41:27.071 --> 00:41:29.320
You're heating the oil, when
you add the whole spices,

00:41:29.320 --> 00:41:31.070
you're infusing the
oil with those flavors

00:41:31.070 --> 00:41:33.889
of the spices, which have
the all-natural oils.

00:41:33.889 --> 00:41:34.930
I can say that 100 times.

00:41:34.930 --> 00:41:35.971
It will be the same line.

00:41:39.550 --> 00:41:41.369
But that is one mistake
which people take.

00:41:41.369 --> 00:41:42.910
When you add powders
in the beginning

00:41:42.910 --> 00:41:44.575
of the cooking
process, you might

00:41:44.575 --> 00:41:45.700
think that that might work.

00:41:45.700 --> 00:41:49.160
But when powders burn, they
become extremely bitter.

00:41:49.160 --> 00:41:51.060
AUDIENCE: That would
explain a lot actually.

00:41:51.060 --> 00:41:52.680
VIKAS KHANNA: That
will explain a lot?

00:41:52.680 --> 00:41:53.930
AUDIENCE: Thank you very much.

00:41:53.930 --> 00:41:55.013
VIKAS KHANNA: My pleasure.

00:42:02.480 --> 00:42:04.040
AUDIENCE: I have
a quick question.

00:42:04.040 --> 00:42:09.300
Sometimes we try to cook,
as like 9-5 working people,

00:42:09.300 --> 00:42:15.230
but when we go to home to cook
dinner, and it's like 8 PM,

00:42:15.230 --> 00:42:18.280
there isn't much
we can cook from.

00:42:18.280 --> 00:42:20.880
And we cannot-- I
can steam broccoli,

00:42:20.880 --> 00:42:25.485
but I cannot cook like
a full Indian turka,

00:42:25.485 --> 00:42:27.870
aloo gobi or like
rajma or something,

00:42:27.870 --> 00:42:31.480
because it takes time to
first put the whole spices

00:42:31.480 --> 00:42:34.650
into the oil, first put the
oil, warm it up, whole spices,

00:42:34.650 --> 00:42:38.240
onions, then bring the turka
in, then put the veggie--

00:42:38.240 --> 00:42:41.480
vegetables, the whole process
kind of takes about how one

00:42:41.480 --> 00:42:42.100
hour.

00:42:42.100 --> 00:42:44.030
So is there like something?

00:42:44.030 --> 00:42:49.500
I tried buy premade
spices, premade gravies,

00:42:49.500 --> 00:42:51.680
and then put them,
that into the oil.

00:42:51.680 --> 00:42:53.710
But it doesn't
smell that well as

00:42:53.710 --> 00:42:59.070
the fresh spices, whole
spices, into the oil smell.

00:42:59.070 --> 00:43:02.579
So is there a trick-- how do,
I'm always amazed, at how do--

00:43:02.579 --> 00:43:04.620
VIKAS KHANNA: I'm telling
you the biggest problem

00:43:04.620 --> 00:43:07.810
is a lot of Indian women.

00:43:07.810 --> 00:43:11.106
They have attained such great
standards of Indian food,

00:43:11.106 --> 00:43:12.980
that sometimes it's hard
for us to beat that.

00:43:12.980 --> 00:43:16.950
I'm talking about--
I'm being honest.

00:43:16.950 --> 00:43:20.580
They make the simplest
potatoes taste like heaven.

00:43:20.580 --> 00:43:22.860
And they seem to be
so without any effort.

00:43:22.860 --> 00:43:23.710
The food is ready.

00:43:23.710 --> 00:43:25.550
It is sitting on the table.

00:43:25.550 --> 00:43:27.970
And the bread magically
comes fully puffed up.

00:43:27.970 --> 00:43:29.030
OK.

00:43:29.030 --> 00:43:32.170
They have raised the
standard of Indian cooking

00:43:32.170 --> 00:43:36.690
so high that they
have destroyed us.

00:43:36.690 --> 00:43:40.302
they're not helping us
anymore, in a very good way.

00:43:40.302 --> 00:43:41.510
You're so right in some ways.

00:43:41.510 --> 00:43:43.080
When we go back
home, I don't want

00:43:43.080 --> 00:43:45.120
to think about making
all this infusions.

00:43:45.120 --> 00:43:46.490
I don't want to do that stuff.

00:43:46.490 --> 00:43:48.082
I agree on that.

00:43:48.082 --> 00:43:49.580
But if you read this book--

00:43:52.630 --> 00:43:55.022
AMAR JOSHI: Plug-in
for the book.

00:43:55.022 --> 00:43:57.230
VIKAS KHANNA: --you'd be
surprised at how easy it is.

00:43:57.230 --> 00:43:58.590
You steam the broccoli, right?

00:43:58.590 --> 00:43:59.910
How much time you stem it for?

00:43:59.910 --> 00:44:00.830
Three to four minutes?

00:44:00.830 --> 00:44:01.670
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:44:01.670 --> 00:44:03.128
